The low thrum of the skyboard beneath Leo\'92s feet did little to soothe the unease coiling in his gut. Hours had passed since the bizarre incident at the convenience store, hours spent soaring between the glittering Sky-Terraces with Max in an attempt to clear his head. Max, predictably, had treated the aerial maneuvers like an extreme sport, whooping as he executed flawless zero-G barrel rolls between cascading waterfalls spilling from floating gardens. Leo had flown mostly on autopilot, the image of the glitch \'96 that burst of angry, jagged rainbow static \'96 replaying behind his eyes, overlaying the perfect cityscape like a visual echo. It wasn't just a flicker; it felt like a momentary puncture in reality. He needed his lab.\
Now, the elevator descended past the lowest public level, the familiar security protocols bypassed with a silent command. It opened into the familiar, controlled chaos of his sanctuary below the city's pristine surface. Holographic schematics already flickered in the air where K-V, his multi-jointed robotic assistant arm, was running preliminary diagnostics Leo had initiated remotely after leaving the store. Discarded prototypes \'96 failed attempts at stabilizing minor energy fluctuations \'96 lay scattered on the benches like metallic skeletons. This was where he could think, where he could dig into the anomaly without interruption.\
He barely had time to shrug off his sleek, wind-resistant flight jacket when the elevator chimed again, announcing Max's arrival. His friend burst in, still buzzing with adrenaline from their skyboarding session, already tearing open a bag of neon-green snack puffs that crackled faintly in the lab's filtered air.\
"Dude, that last inversion loop? Almost clipped a transport drone!" Max grinned, collapsing onto his designated worn sofa with a satisfied sigh, sending puff crumbs scattering across the synth-fabric. "Okay, fun time over, crisis mode engaged. Elara-prime. Zero-G club. Less than an hour." He popped a puff into his mouth. "Operation: Impress."\
Leo was already at his main console, sweeping his hand through holographic displays, pulling up the sparse public sensor logs from the area around the C-Store. As expected, nothing official registered the gunfire, the damage, or the instantaneous repair. Those things just... didn't count, smoothed over by whatever systems kept their world running flawlessly. But the static flicker... that felt 
\f6\i different
\f0\i0 , like a seam splitting. "Crisis mode?" Leo murmured distractedly, filtering the logs for stray electromagnetic fluctuations or unregistered energy signatures near the event time.\
"My date!" Max exclaimed, sitting up straighter, his focus absolute now. "Focus, Leo! I need an edge. Something... subtle. She's amazing, yeah? Got that whole subspace shimmer thing going on. But sometimes you get that feeling, like, is she 
\f6\i really
\f0\i0  listening, or is she composing a witty rejection message under the table? Or what if that slick guy with the chrome implants across the room tries to deploy his 'legendary' charm routine? I need intel! Tactical advantage!"\
Leo turned from the console, the request finally penetrating his preoccupation. Max wasn't asking for a pheromone spray or a flashy conjuration this time; he wanted situational awareness, discreetly. "Intel," Leo mused, tapping a finger against his chin. His mind, accustomed to complex problem-solving, automatically began cycling through options. "Okay. Audio bug? Too risky, easily detected by standard privacy sweeps. Miniature spy drone? Too obvious, even the cloaked ones leave faint energy trails. Hmm." He glanced at K-V, who had paused its diagnostics, rotating its main optical sensor towards them as if awaiting input, processing the conversational parameters.\
"Exactly! Nothing obvious!" Max agreed enthusiastically, leaning forward, elbows on his knees. "It's gotta be stealthy. Like, built into something normal I'd wear anyway. Something cool."\
"Wearable..." Leo's mind caught on a thread. Direct visual feed was complex, requiring sophisticated micro-cameras and transmission protocols. But simple light... "What about light refraction?" he mused aloud. "Bouncing the existing ambient light from a target area back to a localized receiver? Passive observation."\
Max tilted his head, processing. "Like... a periscope? But tiny? Embedded in something?"\
"Essentially," Leo confirmed, an idea solidifying, a potential design already sketching itself in his mind's eye. "We could embed micro-lenses and a focusing crystal into something like a watch. You'd aim it using a reflective surface near your target \'96 maybe the polished tabletop, someone's drink glass, even a shiny utensil."\
Max's eyes lit up. "Yes! That's it! Elegant espionage! Totally Bond-villain tech, but, you know, for navigating the treacherous waters of dating!" He jumped up from the sofa. "Sleek, though, Leo. Gotta look like a high-end timepiece, not some clunky gadget from the History Archives."\
"Sleek it is." Leo moved to a smaller workbench dedicated to rapid prototyping, K-V gliding silently along its ceiling track to hover nearby, auxiliary tool manipulators extending. "K-V, initiate fabrication sequence: Project Night Owl." With focused concentration, Leo began sketching the design in the air with holographic light, dictating components as they materialized from shimmering energy streams. "Primary casing: chrono-alloy, brushed silver finish." A shimmering ingot of metal appeared, hovering, awaiting shaping. "Internal array: three articulating micro-lenses, synthetic sapphire composite..." Tiny, glittering lenses, smaller than a grain of sand, materialized beside the ingot. "Focusing element: Kestral-cut amplification crystal..." A thumbnail-sized, multifaceted crystal shimmered into existence, pulsing faintly. "Power source: miniature cold-fusion cell, shielded, type 7..." A tiny cylinder, glowing with a soft blue light, joined the components.\
K-V's manipulators, tipped with precise lasers and micro-assemblers, went to work with silent efficiency. The chrono-alloy flowed and shaped under the beams like liquid mercury hardening into the watch casing's elegant lines. Max watched, fascinated, leaning over the bench. "Whoa. Okay, okay, can you make the faceplate minimalist? Just abstract light patterns that pulse subtly? Until I activate the refraction thing, then it switches?"\
