rd. Pain flared, sharp and real. Not a dream. Her gaze fixed on the robot, she took a hesitant step closer. It remained perfectly still. Trembling slightly, she extended a hand, palm open, stopping just inches from its smooth chassis. She could feel a faint warmth radiating from it. Then, summoning her courage, she let her fingertips brush against the cool metal. It felt solid. Real. **(Leo's Lab - Intercut):** Leo watched, breathless, his view now intimately close through the Seeker's own optics. He saw the shock on Anya's face, the internal conflict, the cautious extension of her hand, the first tentative touch. It felt incredibly personal, almost invasive, yet he couldn't look away. **(Anya's Cabin):** The robot's head tilted slightly. A calm, synthesized voice, quieter and less imposing than the Core AI\'92s, broke the silence. "Greetings. I am designated Seeker 03255202." Anya snatched her hand back, startled by the voice. "You... you can talk?" "Affirmative," the Seeker replied. "I require assistance. My directive protocols indicate you possess relevant aptitudes. We are in critical need of help." "Help? Help with what?" Anya asked, confusion replacing some of the fear. "Who are 'we'?" "The System I serve is experiencing catastrophic degradation," the Seeker stated, perhaps omitting the full truth about the simulation for now, focusing on the immediate need. "Core functionality is threatened. Trillions of\'85 units\'85 are at risk. We require external intervention. I must interface with your designated community leaders." Anya's eyes widened in alarm, the implications hitting her instantly. Leaders? The camp elders? They'd see a robot, hear 'System', and react with fear, not reason. "No! No way!" she whispered urgently, glancing towards the cabin door. "They won't listen! They'll destroy you the moment they see you! They're terrified of anything like you." The Seeker processed this, its sensors perhaps detecting the genuine fear in her voice. "Negative reaction probability was calculated at 87.3%. However, inaction guarantees mission failure." "There has to be another way," Anya insisted, her mind racing. She looked around her small cabin, then back at the robot. "You need to hide. Here. In my cabin. Give me time. I need to\'85 talk to people. Prepare them somehow. Find a way to make them listen." The Seeker remained still for a moment, calculating. Hiding violated its directive to seek immediate assistance, but Anya's assessment of the danger seemed accurate. Her willingness to help, however cautious, represented the first positive human interaction it had encountered. "Query: Duration estimate for 'preparation'?" "I don't know," Anya admitted honestly. "A few days? Maybe longer? You have to stay completely hidden. No noise, no lights unless I say so. Can you do that?" "Affirmative. Stealth protocols engaged. Awaiting your signal." The Seeker's optical lights dimmed further, and it moved silently towards the darkest corner of the cabin, tucking itself behind a stack of salvaged crates, becoming just another shadow. Anya let out a shaky breath, her heart still pounding. A robot. A talking robot needing help, hiding in her cabin. Her life had just become infinitely more complicated, and dangerous. Later that night, unable to sleep, she found herself whispering to the silent shadow in the corner, partly to process, partly from a lifetime of solitary work. "It's crazy, you know... needing help from us. Everyone's so scared..." She picked up the half-finished robot figure from her desk, the one missing key parts. "All these years, reading those old books... I just wanted to build something. A friend. Like a little robot dog, maybe. Something loyal... that wouldn't run away or get scared." She sighed, placing the figure back down. "Guess wanting a robot friend sounds even crazier now, huh?" In the corner, the Seeker registered the words, logging the emotional data without comment, while miles away, watching through its feed, 