ten, Anya\'85 I've been working on something. While you were busy helping the bots rewire the hydro-dam access grid." He grinned. "Something\'85 for you. Can I show you?" Anya\'92s curiosity piqued, touched by his slight nervousness. "Of course, Leo. What is it?" He didn't answer immediately, just held out his hand. She took it without hesitation, his touch warm, solid, undeniably real within this constructed reality. He led her out of the lab, the simulated environment shifting seamlessly from the industrial feel of his workspace to a stunningly beautiful park environment, meticulously crafted \'96 maybe resembling Central Park as you suggested, with lush greenery, sparkling water, and gentle sunlight filtering through the trees. They walked hand-in-hand along a winding path, the earlier awkwardness replaced by comfortable intimacy. He held a small, elegantly wrapped box in his free hand. They arrived at a picturesque stone bridge, its arches reflected perfectly in the still water below, framing a view of the simulated city skyline in the distance \'96 stable, vibrant, and whole. They stopped in the middle of the bridge, leaning against the cool stone railing, looking out at the idyllic scene. Leo turned to her, his eyes bright. "I remembered," he began, his voice soft, holding out the box. "Back when the Seeker was first hiding in your cabin\'85 before we even really talked\'85 you mentioned wanting a friend. A robot friend." Anya looked up at him, surprised, then deeply touched that he\'92d held onto that small, whispered wish from so long ago, across all the chaos and danger. "I know it's just the simulation," Leo continued, placing the box gently in her hands. "It's not the same as having one in the real world, but\'85 I spent a long time on this. Getting it right. I wanted you to have it." Her fingers trembled slightly as she carefully unwrapped the box. Inside, nestled on a bed of soft, dark velvet, was a small robotic puppy. It was exquisitely crafted, its m